Notes

1. Understanding If-Else Syntax
If-Else statements control the flow of a program by executing specific code blocks based on conditional logic.

C
if (condition1) {
    // Executes if condition1 is true
} 
else if (condition2) {
    // Executes if condition1 is false AND condition2 is true
} 
else {
    // Executes only if all preceding conditions are false
}
2. Basic Comparison Example
When comparing two numbers (int a = 10; int b = 20;):

if (a > b) checking fails because 10 is not greater than 20.

The program automatically jumps to the fallback else block, executing printf("b > a");.

3. Practical Multi-Condition Program: Grading System
To manage multiple numeric brackets cleanly, combine relational operators (>, <, >=) with logical operators. In this context, the Logical AND (&&) operator ensures that a block of code executes only if the input falls correctly within both the lower and upper bounds of a specific range.

Complete Example Program Structure:
C
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    float marks = 0.0;

    printf("Enter your marks: ");
    scanf("%f", &marks);

    if (marks >= 90.0) {
        printf("Your grade is A\n");
    } 
    else if (marks >= 80.0 && marks < 90.0) {
        printf("Your grade is B\n");
    } 
    else if (marks >= 70.0 && marks < 80.0) {
        printf("Your grade is C\n");
    } 
    else if (marks >= 60.0 && marks < 70.0) {
        printf("Your grade is D\n");
    } 
    else {
        printf("Your grade is F\n"); // Triggers automatically if marks are below 60
    }

    return 0;
}
